[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] In machine learning, **feature hashing**, also known as the **hashing trick** (by analogy to the kernel trick), is a fast and space-efficient way of vectorizing features, i.e. turning arbitrary features into indices in a vector or matrix.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] It works by applying a hash function to the features and using their hash values as indices directly (after a modulo operation), rather than looking the indices up in an associative array.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] In addition to its use for encoding non-numeric values, feature hashing can also be used for dimensionality reduction.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] This trick is often attributed to Weinberger et al.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] (2009), but there exists a much earlier description of this method published by John Moody in 1989.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] In a typical document classification task, the input to the machine learning algorithm (both during learning and classification) is free text.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] From this, a bag of words (BOW) representation is constructed: the individual tokens are extracted and counted, and each distinct token in the training set defines a feature (independent variable) of each of the documents in both the training and test sets.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] Machine learning algorithms, however, are typically defined in terms of numerical vectors.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] Therefore, the bags of words for a set of documents is regarded as a term-document matrix where each row is a single document, and each column is a single feature/word; the entry *i*, *j* in such a matrix captures the frequency (or weight) of the j'th term of the *vocabulary* in document i.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] (An alternative convention swaps the rows and columns of the matrix, but this difference is immaterial.) Typically, these vectors are extremely sparse—according to Zipf's law.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] The common approach is to construct, at learning time or prior to that, a *dictionary* representation of the vocabulary of the training set, and use that to map words to indices.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] Hash tables and tries are common candidates for dictionary implementation.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] The problem with this process is that such dictionaries take up a large amount of storage space and grow in size as the training set grows.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] On the contrary, if the vocabulary is kept fixed and not increased with a growing training set, an adversary may try to invent new words or misspellings that are not in the stored vocabulary so as to circumvent a machine learned filter.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] Research attempted to use feature hashing for their spam filters.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] Note that the hashing trick isn't limited to text classification and similar tasks at the document level, but can be applied to any problem that involves large (perhaps unbounded) numbers of features.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] Mathematically, a token is an element t in a finite (or countably infinite) set T .
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] Suppose we only need to process a finite corpus, then we can put all tokens appearing in the corpus into T , meaning that T is finite.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] However, suppose we want to process all possible words made of the English letters, then T is countably infinite.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] Most neural networks can only operate on real vector inputs, so we must construct a "dictionary" function $\phi :T\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] When T is finite, of size $|T|=m\leq n$ , then we can use one-hot encoding to map it into $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] In other words, we assign a unique index i to each token, then map the token with index i to the unit basis vector $e_{i}$ .
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] One-hot encoding is easy to interpret, but it requires one to maintain the arbitrary enumeration of T .
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] Given a token $t\in T$ , to compute $\phi (t)$ , we must find out the index i of the token t .
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] Thus, to implement $\phi$ efficiently, we need a fast-to-compute bijection $h:T\to \{1,...,m\}$ , then we have $\phi (t)=e_{h(t)}$ .
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] In fact, we can relax the requirement slightly: It suffices to have a fast-to-compute *injection* $h:T\to \{1,...,n\}$ , then use $\phi (t)=e_{h(t)}$ .
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] In practice, there is no simple way to construct an efficient injection $h:T\to \{1,...,n\}$ .
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] However, we do not need a strict injection, but only an *approximate* injection.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] That is, when $t\neq t'$ , we should *probably* have $h(t)\neq h(t')$ , so that *probably* $\phi (t)\neq \phi (t')$ .
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] At this point, we have just specified that h should be a hashing function.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] Thus we reach the idea of feature hashing.
