[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] There are essentially only two ways to handle infinities.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] One may impose a metric, then take its completion, to allow well-behaved infinite sums, or one may demand that nothing is actually infinite, only potentially so.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] Here, we go for the potential-infinity way, by restricting $\mathbb {R} ^{T}$ to contain only vectors with finite support: $\forall (x_{t})_{t\in T}\in \mathbb {R} ^{T}$ , only finitely many entries of $(x_{t})_{t\in T}$ are nonzero.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] Taking its completion would get us to a Hilbert space, which allows well-behaved infinite sums.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] Now we have an inner product space, with enough structure to describe the geometry of the feature hashing function $\phi :\mathbb {R} ^{T}\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
