[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] Feature hashing generally suffers from hash collision, which means that there exist pairs of different tokens with the same hash: $t\neq t',\phi (t)=\phi (t')=v$ .
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] A machine learning model trained on feature-hashed words would then have difficulty distinguishing t and $t'$ , essentially because v is polysemic.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] If $t'$ is rare, then performance degradation is small, as the model could always just ignore the rare case, and pretend all v means t .
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] However, if both are common, then the degradation can be serious.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] To handle this, one can train supervised hashing functions that avoids mapping common tokens to the same feature vectors.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] Ganchev and Dredze showed that in text classification applications with random hash functions and several tens of thousands of columns in the output vectors, feature hashing need not have an adverse effect on classification performance, even without the signed hash function.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] (2015) combined the idea of feature hashing and sparse matrix to construct "virtual matrices": large matrices with small storage requirements.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] The idea is to treat a matrix $M\in \mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ as a dictionary, with keys in $n\times n$ , and values in $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] Then, as usual in hashed dictionaries, one can use a hash function $h:\mathbb {N} \times \mathbb {N} \to m$ , and thus represent a matrix as a vector in $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ , no matter how big n is.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/feature-hashing] With virtual matrices, they constructed *HashedNets*, which are large neural networks taking only small amounts of storage.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/locality-sensitive-hashing] In computer science, **locality-sensitive hashing** (**LSH**) is a fuzzy hashing technique that hashes similar input items into the same "buckets" with high probability.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/locality-sensitive-hashing] The number of buckets is much smaller than the universe of possible input items.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/locality-sensitive-hashing] Since similar items end up in the same buckets, this technique can be used for data clustering and nearest neighbor search.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/locality-sensitive-hashing] It differs from conventional hashing techniques in that hash collisions are maximized, not minimized.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/locality-sensitive-hashing] Alternatively, the technique can be seen as a way to reduce the dimensionality of high-dimensional data; high-dimensional input items can be reduced to low-dimensional versions while preserving relative distances between items.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/locality-sensitive-hashing] Hashing-based approximate nearest-neighbor search algorithms generally use one of two main categories of hashing methods: either data-independent methods, such as locality-sensitive hashing (LSH); or data-dependent methods, such as locality-preserving hashing (LPH).
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/locality-sensitive-hashing] Locality-preserving hashing was initially devised as a way to facilitate data pipelining in implementations of massively parallel algorithms that use randomized routing and universal hashing to reduce memory contention and network congestion.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/locality-sensitive-hashing] if it satisfies the following condition.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/locality-sensitive-hashing] Alternatively it is possible to define an LSH family on a universe of items U endowed with a similarity function $\phi \colon U\times U\to [0,1]$ .
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/locality-sensitive-hashing] In this setting, a LSH scheme is a family of hash functions H coupled with a probability distribution D over H such that a function $h\in H$ chosen according to D satisfies $Pr[h(a)=h(b)]=\phi (a,b)$ for each $a,b\in U$ .
