[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/locality-sensitive-hashing] Because the symmetric group on n elements has size n!, choosing a truly random permutation from the full symmetric group is infeasible for even moderately sized n.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/locality-sensitive-hashing] Because of this fact, there has been significant work on finding a family of permutations that is "min-wise independent" — a permutation family for which each element of the domain has equal probability of being the minimum under a randomly chosen π.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/locality-sensitive-hashing] It has been established that a min-wise independent family of permutations is at least of size $\operatorname {lcm} \{\,1,2,\ldots ,n\,\}\geq e^{n-o(n)}$ , and that this bound is tight.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/locality-sensitive-hashing] Because min-wise independent families are too big for practical applications, two variant notions of min-wise independence are introduced: restricted min-wise independent permutations families, and approximate min-wise independent families.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/locality-sensitive-hashing] Restricted min-wise independence is the min-wise independence property restricted to certain sets of cardinality at most k.
[src:locality-sensitive-hashing/locality-sensitive-hashing] Approximate min-wise independence differs from the property by at most a fixed ε.
